Nations back WHO antimicrobial resistance global action plan
----field----
field: {446A339B-E1D9-4DE1-8B5E-DB7942EF1723}
name: Body
key: body
content-length: 3014

<p>Members states of the World Health Organization (WHO) have agreed to adopt a global action plan against antimicrobial resistance (AMR), which calls for new concepts to provide incentives for innovation and promote the cooperation between policymakers, academia and the pharmaceutical industry to ensure new technologies are available globally to prevent, diagnose and treat resistant infections. </p><p>The plan, which was drawn up by WHO, calls for improving awareness and understanding of AMR; strengthening surveillance and research; reducing the incidence of infection; optimizing the use of antimicrobial medicines; and ensuring sustainable investment.</p><p>At the annual meeting in Geneva of the World Health Assembly (WHA), the decision-making body of WHO, each of the member nations committed to having their own plans in place by May 2017 that align with the global AMR blueprint.</p><p>In urging the WHA delegates to adopt the global AMR action plan, WHO Director-General Dr Margaret Chan last week had warned about the possibility of a "post-antibiotic era, in which common infections will once again kill."</p><p>At the WHA meeting, which concluded on 26 May, German Chancellor Angela Merkel noted that her own cabinet had just recently adopted its own strategy, which she said would require close cooperation in the fields of human and veterinary medicine.</p><p>Health and Human Services Secretary Sylvia Mathews Burwell also pointed out the US unveiled a <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/US-Capitol-Capsule-Obama-superbug-attack-plan-hinges-on-funding-cooperation-357553" target="_new">five-year AMR plan in March</a>, the <i>National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria</i>, which was developed in response to an executive order issued by President Barack Obama on 18 September 2014.</p><p>The US plan outlines the steps for implementing Mr Obama's <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/Obama-launches-multi-strategy-attack-on-antibiotic-resistance-354030" target="_new">multi-pronged strategy</a> for attacking AMR and addressing the policy recommendations from the President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology Policy, the details of which were first disclosed at a meeting in <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/US-Capitol-Capsule-Staying-ahead-of-tricky-resistant-bugs-PCAST-outlines-path-352852" target="_new">July 2014</a>, with the final report issued two months later.</p><p>At the WHA meeting, Secretary Burwell also revealed the White House plans to hold a forum on 2 June with various stakeholders, including biopharmaceutical manufacturers, with the goal of exchanging ideas on the ways public- and private-sector organizations can collaborate to improve responsible antibiotic use and discussing opportunities for further improvement &ndash; a <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/Superbug-summit-White-House-to-hold-antibiotics-forum-358474" target="_new">superbug summit</a>.</p><p><p><p><p><p><p><p><p>
